ce:section.ce:para:
The gas sensing parameters of carbon QDs-containing structures are reported in Table 3
                        . Graphene QDs were also used in the architecture of composite structures to develop flexible gas sensing devices. The nitrogen-doped (N-doped) graphene QDs enhanced the response of poly (3,4-ethylenedioxythiophene)–poly (styrenesulfonate) (PEDOT–PSS) sensors towards CH3OH by an order of magnitude [161]. The response time of N-doped graphene QDs/PEDOT–PSS composite and PEDOT–PSS towards 100 ppm of CH3OH was 12 and 164 s, respectively. The resistance of N-doped graphene QDs/PEDOT–PSS was completely recovered to its initial value after the pure air exposure for 40 s, while the PEDOT–PSS structure exhibited resistance drift. Furthermore, the interaction of PEDOT–PSS with CH3OH is exothermic and the desorption rate of CH3OH molecules at higher temperatures is faster than their adsorption rate. Therefore, the composite material was more sensitive to CH3OH at RT. In addition, the N-doped QDs formed conduction channels in the PEDOT–PSS matrix improving the charge transport characteristics of the material. Another flexible structure based on sulfur (S) and N co-doped graphene QDs and polyaniline (PANI) showed a similar trend. The response of S–N–graphene QDs/PANI sensor towards 100 ppm of NH3 was five times higher than that of the pristine PANI [162]. Meanwhile, the composite material was not sensitive towards different volatile organic compounds (VOCs) indicating its high selectivity to NH3 (Fig. 12
                        ). It is worth noting that the concentration of dopants in graphene QDs and the concentration of carbon QDs in the polymer matrix may affect the sensing performance of the final device [163,164]. For example, N-doped graphene QDs/PEDOT–PSS composite showed an optimal response towards NH3 at 50 wt% of N-doped QDs [163]. However, when the operating temperature of the structure was increased from 25 to 80 °C, the polymer matrix was expanded affecting the transport of charge carriers and functionalities of sensors.
